<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900712-0121</DOCNO><DOCID>900712-0121.</DOCID><HL>   Greenspan Supports Move   Requiring Budget Balance</HL><DATE>07/12/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><GV>FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Federal Reserve Board Chairman AlanGreenspan told a House panel that America's fiscal problemshave become so severe that he reluctantly supports aconstitutional amendment requiring a balanced federal budget.   In 1979, as a private economist, Mr. Greenspan testifiedagainst a proposal for a balanced-budget amendment. &quot;At thetime, I was skeptical it could work,&quot; he said. But now, hetold the House Judiciary Committee yesterday: &quot;The crucialissue that I think creates the desire for a balance-budgetamendment is the bias that clearly exists in our systemtoward deficits.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The &quot;very serious gridlock&quot; Congress and administrationofficials have encountered in trying to reduce the country'smassive budget deficit during the past few years, Mr.Greenspan said, &quot;suggests there is something in our systemthat needs to be redressed, and I'd say regrettably byconstitutional means.&quot;   Mr. Greenspan didn't endorse a specific amendment but didrecommend a provision requiring more than a majority vote inCongress to pass spending bills. He emphasized that he wasexpressing his personal views and not those of the Fed.</TEXT></DOC>